- December: 1st case
Date: Mon 15 Feb 2021
Source: Guinee Matin [abridged, edited]
https://guineematin.com/2021/02/15/reapparition-du-virus-ebola-en-guinee-le-cas-a-commence-en-debut-decembre-2020-a-nzerekore-drs/


As previously announced, Ebola haemorrhagic disease has reappeared in Guinea. Already, it has killed at least 3 people in the southern region of the country where the 1st cases have been recorded, especially in the sub-prefecture of Gouecke, prefecture of N'Zerekore.

The resurgence of this disease in this region led the administrative and health authorities of N'Zerekore to hold yesterday, Sun 14 Feb2021, a "health emergency meeting" which resulted in the implementation of a response plan. And, at the end of this meeting, Dr H Sira Guilavogui, in charge of training, planning and research at the regional health directorate of N'Zerekore, revealed that the reappearance of the Ebola virus dates back to the very beginning of December 2020, reports the correspondent of https://Guineematin.com in the capital of the forest region.

According to the training, planning and research officer at the N'Zerekore regional health directorate, the causes of the resurgence of the Ebola virus in Guinea are not yet known. However, Dr H Sira Guilavogui specifies that it was at the beginning of last December [2020] that the previously known zero patient (a 51-year-old nurse) presented to the Gouecke health center with vomiting and diarrhea. The diagnosis which had been made to him had then concluded to a severe anemia.

"On 12 Feb 2021, we were informed by the director of the hospital of the arrival of some suspicious cases; and, immediately, the DPS and the DRS, went to the bedside of these patients. Samples were taken and sent to Gouecke and Conakry for analysis. But the investigation team continued to Gouecke where the suspected cases resided. In the field, during the investigation, we also noted another case which was sick in the family. He was transferred to the hospital. But, as of today, we have 2 cases who are hospitalized at the CT-EPI in N'Zerekore. A case that was referred to Conakry and 2 cases that died and whose bodies are in the N'Zerekore morgue, are awaiting a dignified and secure burial.

This is because the case began in early December 2020 when the old woman (51-year-old nurse) presented to the Gouecke health center. But, the diagnosis that was made was a diagnosis of severe anemia. She was hospitalized for 5 days at the health center and was released. And, a few days later, she passed away. In the meantime, her sister-in-law who looked after her during her convalescence also developed the same approximate signs as the old woman. And, over time, she, too, passed away. This is how the other members of the family (brothers and sisters) also saw themselves in the same picture," explained Dr HSira Guilavogui.

To contain this disease and prevent its spread throughout the N'Zerekore prefecture, "urgent measures" have just been taken by the local authorities. And, among these provisions, there is in particular the establishment of a "belt of struggle" to identify, locate and isolate all contacts in Gouecke.

"Urgent arrangements have been made; and, within the framework of the application of these provisions, we met this morning so that all the points which were found or omitted are re-established, that each one is operational on the ground. That is why we held this meeting so that already at the level of Gouecke, we constitute a form of belt for the fight against this disease by seeking all contacts. The suspected cases, the confirmed cases that all these contacts are revealed and that they are located somewhere to prevent them from spreading the disease. I would like to ask the population not to panic, to play the games of the services of health and games for all those who are concerned by the fight against this disease to prevent it from spreading throughout the country," said Saa Yola Tolno.

[Byline: Foromo Gbouo Lamah]

