******
[2] DRC (North Kivu)

- ECDC (European Center for Disease Control): epidemiological update
Date: Mon 15 Feb 2021
Source: ECDC [abridged, edited]
https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/news-events/ebola-virus-disease-nzerekore-guinea-february-2021


On 14 Feb 2021, an Ebola virus disease (EVD) outbreak was declared in the rural area of Gouecke in N'Zerekore region, Guinea, by national health authorities. Three laboratory-confirmed cases have been confirmed by the national reference laboratory, the 1st confirmed cases reported since 2016.

According to the World Health Organization's Regional Office for Africa and the Ministry of Health of Guinea, on 28 Jan 2021, a healthcare worker from Gouecke Health Center died. Six people who attended his funeral on 1 Feb 2021 later began to show Ebola-like symptoms (diarrhoea, vomiting and bleeding). Two of these cases have since died, and the other 4 have been hospitalised.

According to Agence Nationale de Securite Sanitaire-ANSS, one of the 4 hospitalised cases is currently in isolation at a healthcare facility in Conakry, while the other 3 have been isolated in Gouecke, N'Zerekore region.

Samples from the confirmed cases have been sent to the Institut Pasteur in Senegal for full genome sequencing in order to identify the strain of the Ebola virus.

Response measures have been initiated and the World Health Organization (WHO) is supporting Guinea in procuring the EVD vaccine. As the outbreak is located in a border area, WHO is also liaising with health authorities from Liberia and Sierra Leone to enhance surveillance activities in their districts bordering Guinea, as well as strengthening their testing capacity and conducting surveillance at health facilities. WHO is also in contact with Cote d'Ivoire, Mali, Senegal and other countries at risk in the sub-region. According to media sources, Sierra Leone has upgraded its health emergency response plan and the border with Guinea has been closed.

There is a risk that cases may flare up in Guinea. The information currently available is insufficient to be able to confidently assess the likelihood of further or more widespread transmission. Continuing response measures and follow-up of survivors are essential to detect and interrupt transmission early on. Response measures may be jeopardised by other outbreaks in the country.

Significant developments have been made in the prevention of Ebola virus disease, with 2 vaccines now licensed for use in several countries. Assuming that healthcare workers (including EU/EEA citizens that could be deployed in response to this outbreak) are vaccinated and adhere to recommended precautionary measures, the risk of them becoming infected is low.

For other EU/EEA citizens living in or travelling through Guinea, the likelihood of exposure is very low, as is the likelihood of introduction and further spread of the Ebola virus within the EU/EEA.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), Burundi, Ghana and Zambia have licensed the Ebola vaccine Ervebo. The injectable Ebola vaccine is manufactured by Merck (known as MSD outside the US and Canada.

The Ebola virus (Zaire ebolavirus) vaccine is a replication-competent, live, attenuated recombinant vesicular stomatitis virus (rVSV) vaccine. It is also known as V920, rVSVIG-ZEBOV-GP or rVSV-ZEBOV; brand name ERVEBOÃ‚ and manufactured by Merck. It contains a gene for the EBOV glycoprotein that replaces the gene for the native VSV glycoprotein.

Preliminary study results have shown a 97.5% vaccine efficacy. Data also suggests that vaccinating people who are already infected reduces their chances of dying.

The vaccine was approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) on 19 Dec 2019 for the prevention of EVD caused by EBOV in people 18 years of age and older, based on the data from 12 clinical trials that included a total of 15 399 adults (WHO and CDC).

"In the event of an outbreak in the near future, doses of rVSV delta G-ZEBOV-GP would be available from different sources. Researchers in West Africa have a few thousand doses left from the trials, currently stored under Good Clinical Practices conditions. The manufacturer reported that there are a few thousand doses in stock that are owned by the US Biomedical Advanced Research and Development Authority. In addition, the manufacturer committed to produce 300 000 doses for GAVI Alliance through an Advance Procurement Commitment (APC)." (Excerpted from https://www.who.int/immunization/sage/meetings/2018/october/2_Ebola_SAGE2018Oct_BgDoc_20180919.pdf). - Mod.LK]

------
- Vaccine operational
Date: 15 Feb 2021
Source: Radio Okapi [Google trans. edited]
https://www.radiookapi.net/2021/02/15/actualite/sante/ebola-butembo-le-vaccin-deja-operationnel-dans-la-zone-de-sante-de-biena


During an interview granted Sat 13 Feb 2021 to Radio Okapi, the provincial minister of health, Dr Nzanzu Salita affirmed that the vaccine has already started in the health zone of Biena, without specifying the day of its start. He also indicated that this vaccine could spread to other health zones shortly.

Among the other actions already carried out, the Provincial Minister of Health cites, among others, the disinfection of homes and health structures frequented by patients:

"The actions that have already been carried out, the households have been decontaminated, the healthcare structures, in particular the health center of Masoya, decontaminated; we have already listed the contacts, and our teams are hard at work to be able to carry out other actions with the community so that it understands that, here we are, we still have a threat and that we all must unite, work hand in hand to contain this epidemic as quickly as possible."

In addition, the Minister also speaks of an Ebola treatment center set up and where the 22-year-old patient is currently isolated. He adds that 260 contacts for all 3 registered cases are being followed up for 21 days and the listing continues.

Within the community, he admits, some inhabitants of Butembo are still skeptical about this new wave of Ebola, others on the other hand say they understand the danger:

"It's a disappointment really because we thought that Ebola was already over, and here we are again, Ebola is coming back, now that corona is already there too, so I don't know how we are going to deal with all this."

For his part, the Mayor of the city of Butembo Sylvain Kanyamanda indicates that meetings are multiplying with all the partners to make the necessary arrangements to quickly control this disease.

A week after the declaration of the new wave of Ebola virus disease in the Butembo-Lubero region, 3 cases have already been notified including 2 deaths and a patient currently being treated in Butembo. In addition, more than 200 contact cases are being followed up, reports the Provincial Minister of Health.

--
